            <div type="paratext">
                <head>Romantic Revolutions in Europe: an Eight-Day Teaching Unit</head>



                <p rend="noCount"><hi rend="bold">Required Text</hi>: <title level="m">Longman
                        Anthology of British Literature: the Romantics and their
                        Contemporaries</title>, eds. Susan Wolfson and Peter Manning, vol. 2A (New
                    York: Longman, 2003)</p>

                <list type="simple">
                    <item>
                        <anchor xml:id="n1"/><hi rend="bold">Day 1:</hi>
                        <hi rend="bold">Introduction to Romantic Movement</hi>
                    </item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: &quot;The Romantics and their
                        Contemporaries,&quot; 1-29; <name ref="BlakeWilliam">W. Blake</name>:
                        &quot;All Religions are One,&quot; &quot;There is No Natural Religion,&quot;
                        112-18; Biographies of the Godwin Circle (<name ref="WollstonecraftMary">M.
                            Wollstonecraft</name>, 227-29; Godwin, 91; <name
                            ref="ShelleyMaryWollstonecraft">Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley</name>,
                        992-94; <name ref="ShelleyPercyBysshe">P. B. Shelley</name> 752-54)</item>

                    <item>
                        <anchor xml:id="n2"/><hi rend="bold">Day 2: The French Revolution</hi>
                    </item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: <name
                            ref="WilliamsHelenMaria">Helen Maria Williams</name>, <title level="m"
                            >Letters Written in France</title>, 56-66; <name ref="BurkeEdmund"
                            >Edmund Burke</name>, <title level="m">Reflections on the Revolution in
                            France</title>, 67-76; Thomas Paine, <title level="m">The Rights of
                            Man</title>, 84-91; <name ref="ColeridgeSamuelTaylor">Coleridge</name>,
                        &quot;Jacobinism&quot; and &quot;Once a Jacobin Always a Jacobin&quot;
                        582-86; <name ref="WollstonecraftMary">Mary Wollstonecraft</name>, <title
                            level="m">A Vindication of the Rights of Men</title>, 76-84; Godwin,
                            <title level="m">An Enquiry Concerning Political Justice</title>,
                        91-96</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">External links</hi>: France&#39;s <title
                            level="m">Declaration of Rights of Man and Citizen</title>; U.S. <title
                            level="m">Declaration of Independence</title></item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">In-class Writing assignment</hi>: Write a
                        dramatic sketch between <name ref="BurkeEdmund">Burke</name> and <name
                            ref="WollstonecraftMary">Wollstonecraft</name> in pairs. Your setting is
                        a coffeehouse, where the two meet by chance and discuss the French
                        Revolution.</item>

                    <item><anchor xml:id="n3"/><hi rend="bold">Day 3</hi>: The French Revolution and English Dramatic
                        Writing</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: Hannah More, <title level="m"
                            >Village Politics</title>, 100-107; <name ref="ShelleyPercyBysshe">P. B.
                            Shelley</name>, <title level="m">The Cenci</title> (online: Acts I-V);
                        &quot;England in 1819,&quot; 761</item>

                    <item>
                        <anchor xml:id="n4"/><hi rend="bold">Day 4:</hi>
                        <hi rend="bold">The Woman Question</hi>
                    </item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: <name
                            ref="WollstonecraftMary">Mary Wollstonecraft</name>, <title level="m">A
                            Vindication of the Rights of Woman</title>, 229-54; Anna Letitia
                        Barbauld, &quot;The Rights of Woman,&quot; 272-73, <name ref="SoutheyRobert"
                            >R. Southey</name>, &quot;To Mary Wollstonecraft,&quot; 273-74, R.
                        Polwhele, &quot;The Unsex&#39;d Females,&quot; 275-80; Mary Ann Radcliffe,
                            <title level="m">The Female Advocate</title>, 284-90; Hannah More,
                            <title level="m">Strictures on the Modern System of Female
                            Education</title>, 291-97; <name ref="LambMary">Mary Lamb</name>, <title
                            level="m">Letter to The British Lady&#39;s Magazine</title></item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">In-class Writing Assignment on Online
                            Discussion Board</hi> (Blackboard.com):</item>

                    <item rend="indent2">Half of the class (last names A-L) should write an
                        &quot;Anti-Jacobin&quot; response to either <name ref="WollstonecraftMary"
                            >Wollstonecraft</name>&#39;s <title level="m">A Vindication of the
                            Rights of Men</title> or <title level="m">A Vindication of the Rights of
                            Woman</title>, Godwin&#39;s <title level="m">An Enquiry Concerning
                            Political Justice</title>, or Paine&#39;s <title level="m">Rights of
                            Man</title>, taking on the persona of a contemporary parson for the
                        Church of England, Richard Polwhele, <name ref="BurkeEdmund">Edmund
                            Burke</name>, Hannah More, or another persona of your choosing. The
                        other half of the class should respond to these critiques in the personae of
                            <name ref="WollstonecraftMary">Wollstonecraft</name>, Godwin, or
                        Paine.</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">External Links</hi>: Olympe de Gouges
                        (online), <title level="m">Declaration of the Rights of Woman and the Female
                            Citizen</title>; Mary Robinson (online), <title level="m">A Letter to
                            the Women of England</title>, eds. Adriana Craciun, Anne Irmen Close,
                        Megan Musgrave, and Orianne Smith</item>

                    <item><anchor xml:id="n5"/><hi rend="bold">Day 5</hi>: Women &amp; Revolution</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: <name ref="InchbaldMrs."
                            >Elizabeth Inchbald</name>, <title level="m">The Massacre</title>
                        (online: Acts I-III), eds. <name ref="CrochunisThomasC">Thomas C.
                            Crochunis</name> and Michael Eberle-Sinatra, with an Introduction by
                        Danny O&#39;Quinn. <title level="m">British Women Playwrights around
                            1800</title>. 15 April 1999</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">External links</hi>: Daniel J. O&#39;Quinn,
                        &quot;Elizabeth <name ref="InchbaldMrs.">Inchbald</name>&#39;s <title
                            level="m">The Massacre</title>: Tragedy, Violence and the Network of
                        Political Fantasy,&quot; (online) <title level="m">British Women Playwrights
                            around 1800</title>. 1 June 1999.</item>

                    <item><anchor xml:id="n6"/><hi rend="bold">Day 6</hi>: Slavery and Abolitionism in England</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: Olaudah Equiano, <title
                            level="m">The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah
                            Equiano</title>, 159-69; Mary Prince, <title level="m">The History of
                            Mary Prince, a West Indian Slave</title>, 169-74; <name
                            ref="BlakeWilliam">William Blake</name>, &quot;Little Black Boy,&quot;
                        121 and &quot;The Chimney Sweeper,&quot; 122; <name ref="WordsworthDorothy"
                            >Dorothy Wordsworth</name>, Thomas Clarkson, <name
                            ref="WordsworthWilliam">William Wordsworth</name> on slavery and
                        abolitionism, 198-213</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">External Links</hi>: <title level="m">Born
                            in Slavery: Slave Narratives from the Federal Writers&#39; Project,
                            1936-1938</title> at the Library of Congress, Bruce Fort&#39;s resources
                        on American Slave Narratives, <title level="m">Focus on the Slave
                            Trade</title> at BBC Online</item>

                    <item><anchor xml:id="n7"/><hi rend="bold">Day 7</hi>: Slavery and Abolitionism in France</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">Reading</hi>: Olympe de Gouges, &quot;Black
                        Slavery, or the Happy Shipwreck&quot; from <title level="m">Translating
                            Slavery: Gender and Race in French Women&#39;s Writing,
                            1783-1823</title>, trans. Maryann Dejulio, eds. Doris Kadish and
                        Françoise Massardier-Kenney, (Kent, Ohio and London: The Kent State UP,
                        1994), 87-132.</item>

                    <item rend="indent2"><hi rend="bold">External links</hi>: <title level="m"
                            >Touissant l&#39;Ouverture: a Biography and Autobiography</title></item>

                    <item><anchor xml:id="n8"/><hi rend="bold">Day 8</hi>: Essay on <hi rend="bold">Romantic
                            Revolutionaries and their Personae</hi> or <hi rend="bold">Revolutionary
                            Violence and Romantic Drama</hi> due</item>
                </list>
            </div>
